Why doesn't the Fed do its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the US central bank Federal Reserve gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious, first question to be asked is how it was possible that the Fed failed so badly in its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
That the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Now, undoubtedly, institutional soul-searching is in order.
While interest rate policy makes headlines, the Fed is now mainly significant as a financial regulator.
Another big question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to drive climate or social policy forward.
The Fed could, for example, deny loans to companies in the fossil energy sector, require banks to only grant loans to companies with certified net zero emission plans, or direct lending towards desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to take its regulatory activity explicitly in the name of equality or ethnic justice, by instructing banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who should be fired, and so on.
However, before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will move or should move, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's significant failure.
The US government made a fateful decision in 2008: Financial institutions could still obtain the funds for risky investments mainly through the sale of short-term, highly susceptible debt securities, but hordes of new supervisory authorities would henceforth assess the risk susceptibility of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook the large blocks on the bank balance sheets similar in size to the subprime mortgage loans.
However, in the following ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the event of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred in early 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, commercial banks proved to be unable to act as intermediaries on the market for ordinary US government bonds.
The Fed thus supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. Corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been put off until later.
Later there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
The Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported the prices of corporate bonds by essentially providing a guarantee with the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury Department objected to the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the bailout package for the financial sector - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, one had invoked a clear floor for the prices of corporate bonds with the "Powell put", among other things.
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the US Ministry of Finance will simply wipe out each new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives that have created these strategies.
Why bother and use cash or balance room for purchases at falling prices, to provide liquidity or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will simply overdo it and reap the profits.
Why would a company still issue stocks when it can simply take on a loan knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
Why would an investor hesitate to buy dubious papers when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder America is drowning in debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will take on the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages pile up and wait for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
However, each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put in more money into rescue actions and people will not be pleased with billions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages that everyone was expecting do not materialize, we will wake up in a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, at least, regulatory authorities and lawmakers recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, one only succumbed to self-satisfaction over the rescue actions.
Exactly the Fed that in 2008 did not see the risks of subprime mortgages any more than the pandemic of 2020 and will now conduct stress tests in view of "climate risks" will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about the aforementioned events.
And although word salads about "interconnections", "strategic interactions", "network effects", and "credit cycles" are produced, it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk at all, except that it has become a catch-all term that grants regulatory bodies all-encompassing power.
Regulatory bodies will never be able to foresee risks, measure the assets of financial institutions precisely, or ensure that immense debts can always be paid.
We must turn the fundamental premise of the financial system around, in which the state always stands firmly behind debt mountains in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge partisan trenches.
The Left is right when it says that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that bring little benefit to most Americans.
However, it starts from the wrong cause.
A tremendous effort to comply with regulations is a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory determinations are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of rules.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to possess clairvoyant abilities.
The Fed scandalously stopped businesses in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before they devote themselves to the rescue of the planet and the rectification of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
